external_knowledge:
"notable shadow cast upon its valuation accuracy" refers to log_error > 0.1;
"eye of the storm" is a metaphor for the property's ID being the focus (property_id = 1);
"geographical coordinates" refers to the latitude of the property;
"view count" refers to the number of view accesses;
"median sales price" and "estimated worth" refer to the property's financial metrics;
"tumultuous sea of pricing" is another way of referring to significant log_error;

sql:
SELECT property_id
FROM property_market_data
WHERE median_sales_price > 850000;

SELECT property_id, AVG(valuation_amount) AS avg_valuation
FROM property_valuation_history
GROUP BY property_id;

external_knowledge:
- Log error is a measure of valuation accuracy where a lower value indicates a more accurate valuation;
- "Carried by each type of property" metaphorically refers to the average tax amount per property type;
- "Sailing smoothly on the sea of valuation accuracy where log errors are calm and under 0.1" symbolizes the condition where log error must be less than or equal to 0.1;
- "Tax figures follow the alphabetical order of the property types" indicates sorting the results by property type in ascending alphabetical order.

sql:
SELECT AVG(tax_amount) AS average_tax_amount
FROM properties
WHERE region_id_county = 1;

SELECT pal.property_id, pal.access_date, pvh.valuation_amount
FROM property_access_logs pal
JOIN property_valuation_history pvh ON pal.property_id = pvh.property_id;
